1 Data & package loading

First, we import the weather data. It spans the period 1980-2024 at the daily frequency.

Code 
library(tidyverse)     # Data wrangling

library(broom)         # Neat regression output
library(tidyfit)       # Rolling regressions
library(patchwork)     # Plot layout

ewma <- function (x, ratio) {
  c(stats::filter(x * ratio, 1 - ratio, "recursive", init = x[1]))
}

impute <- function(v, n = 12){     # Imputation function
  for(j in 1:n){
    ind <- which(is.na(v))
    if(length(ind)>0){
      if(ind[1]==1){ind <- ind[-1]}
      v[ind] <- v[ind-1]
    }
  }
  return(v)
}

  rename(date = time) |>
  mutate(date = as.Date(date))

3 First attempt for an extreme weather index

Next, we define thresholds that will determine what âextremeâ means. For each state and metric, the threshold is the 2% level, meaning a scenario that occurs once every 50 days. Henceforth, the notations are as follows: \(t\) is the time index and \(s\) the state index.
We focus on 4 situations:

  • abnormaly high maximum temperature \(T^+_{t,s}\) (very warm days);
  • abnormaly low minimum temperature \(T^-_{t,s}\) (very cold days);
  • extreme daily precipitation \(P_{t,s}\) (very rainy days);
  • extreme average wind speed \(W_{t,s}\) during the day (potential storm) - maximum speed during the day is much less reported.

The corresponding state-specific thresholds (quantiles) are written \(q^+_s\), \(q_s^-\), \(q^P_s\) and \(q_s^W\).

NOTE: there is a trade-off inherent to the threshold level. The more conservative it is (more extreme), the fewer the number of days with nonzero scores.

Below, we depict the thresholds for all states (when available).

Code 
thresh <- 0.02
date_thresh <- "2005-01-01"
data_thresh <- data |>
  filter(date < date_thresh) |>
  mutate(month = month(date)) |>
  group_by(state) |>
  summarise(t_low = quantile(tmin, thresh, na.rm = T),
            t_high = quantile(tmax, 1-thresh, na.rm = T),
            p_high = quantile(prcp, 1-thresh, na.rm = T),
            w_high = quantile(wspd, 1-thresh, na.rm = T))

g1 <- data_thresh |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = t_low, y = reorder(state, t_low))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#338EE3", alpha = 0.7) + theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.title = element_blank(),
        title = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold")) + 
  ggtitle("Minimum temp. threshold (Â°C)")
g2 <- data_thresh |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = t_high, y = reorder(state, t_high))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#FF7800", alpha = 0.7) + theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.title = element_blank(),
        title = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold")) + 
  ggtitle("Maximum temp. threshold (Â°C)")
g3 <- data_thresh |>

Then, based on these quantiles, we craft a metric that measures extreme daily weather across all states (when data is available).
The formula is the following: \[I_t = \sum_{s=1}^{50} \text{gdp}_s\left(1_{T_{t,s}^+>q^+_s}+0.5\times 1_{T_{t,s}^-<q^-_s}+1_{W_{t,s}>q^W_s}+1_{P_{t,s}>q_s^P} \right),\] where \(\text{gdp}_s\) is the relative weight in GDP of state \(s\) (measured in 2022). Indeed, we seek to measure the economic or financial impact, hence GDP is a relevant weighting measure. These weights sum to one. There is a 0.5 scaling factor for very low temperatures. This is to bring balance between extreme cold & hot events. Without this constant, the top 12 events occur during the winter. Perhaps because winter storms score on 3 items (cold + precipitation/snow + wind).

We also test an Exponentially Weighted Moving Average version to see if a smoother version of the index may be useful (spoiler: not so much).

Below, we plot the full series (left), as well as a zoom on the latest 63 days (right) - in 2024.

Code 
min_index <- 0.00
index <- data |> 
  left_join(data_thresh, by = "state") |>
  left_join(states |> select(state, GDP), by = "state") |>
  mutate(temp_up = tmax > t_high,
         temp_down = tmin < t_low,
         rain = prcp > p_high,
         wind = wspd > w_high,
  ) |>
  group_by(date) |>
  mutate(weight = GDP / sum(GDP)) |>
  summarise(index = sum(weight*(temp_up+temp_down*0.5+rain+wind), na.rm = T)) |>
  mutate(index = if_else(index==0, min_index, index),
         index_ewma = ewma(index, 0.8))

A snapshot at extreme events. All of them

4 Link with financial returns

We first fetch the data. Two indices: SPY for equities and IUAG.L for bonds.
Because of the availability of the latter, the analysis only starts in 2011.

Code 
library(quantmod)
tickers <- c("SPY", "IUAG.L")  
# Tickers: Apple, Boeing, Citigroup, Pfizer, Walmart, Exxon
# Others: , "F", "DIS", "GE", "CVX", "MSFT", "GS")
min_date <- "2000-01-01"                      # Starting date
max_date <- "2024-05-27"                      # Ending date
prices <- getSymbols(tickers, src = 'yahoo',  # The data comes from Yahoo Finance
                     from = min_date,         # Start date
                     to = max_date,           # End date
                     auto.assign = TRUE, 
                     warnings = FALSE) %>% 
  map(~Ad(get(.))) %>%                        # Retrieving the data
  reduce(merge) %>%                           # Merge in one dataframe
  `colnames<-`(tickers) %>%                   # Set the column names
  #to.monthly(indexAt = "lastof", OHLC = FALSE) %>%      # Convert to monthly 
  data.frame(date = index(.)) %>%             # Convert the index to a date
  remove_rownames() %>%                       # Remove index => converted into row names
  mutate_all(impute) |>                       # Impute
  na.omit()                                   # Remove missing points

tail(prices,7)                                # Have a look at the result!
Code 
returns <- prices %>%                                    # Start from prices
  pivot_longer(-date, names_to = "Asset", 
               values_to = "Price") %>%                  # Put the data in 'tidy' format
  group_by(Asset) %>%                                    # Group the rows by asset to compute returns
  mutate(return_01 = lead(Price) / Price - 1,            # Compute the returns 
         return_05 = lead(Price, 5) / Price - 1,
         return_21 = lead(Price, 21) / Price - 1) %>%   
  ungroup() |>
  pivot_longer(Price:return_21, names_to = "var", values_to = "value") 

rm(SPY, IUAG.L)

A few full-sample regression results below.

Code 
data_reg <- returns |> 
  left_join(index, by = "date") |>
  mutate(d_index = index - lag(index),
         index_2 = index^2)

data_reg %>% filter(var != "Price") %>% group_by(Asset, var) %>% 
  do(tidy(lm(value ~ index, data = .))) |> filter(term == "index")

The results are not very impressive, especially for equities. Only one case seems promising: 1m forward bond returns.
Letâs move to dynamic rolling regressions. We take 21 day samples.

Code 
# bind_cols(data_reg,
#           roll_lm(x = data_reg$index, 
#                   y = data_reg$SPY, 
#                   width = 21, 
#                   intercept = TRUE)$coefficients
# ) |>
#   ggplot(aes(x = date, y = x1)) + geom_line() + theme_classic()
Code 
roll_reg <- data_reg |>
  filter(var != "Price") |>
  group_by(Asset, var) %>%
  regress(value ~ index,
          m("lm"),# vcov. = "HAC"),
          .cv = "sliding_index", 
          .cv_args = list(lookback = days(21), step = 5, index = "date"),
          .force_cv = TRUE, 
          .return_slices = TRUE)

To show relevance, we plot \(t\)-statistics, with 5% significance levels.

Code 
df_beta <- coef(roll_reg)
df_beta <- df_beta %>% 
  unnest(model_info) %>% 
  mutate(upper = estimate + 2 * std.error, lower = estimate - 2 * std.error)

df_beta |> 
  mutate(date = as.Date(slice_id)) %>%
  filter(term == "index") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = statistic)) + geom_line() + theme_classic() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 2, color = "red", linetype = 2) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = -2, color = "red", linetype = 2) + ggtitle("Equity index") +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(var), cols = vars(Asset), scales = "free")
